<BaseLayout title="Context" active="context" description="Context for Macbeth that adds to the effect: the historical, social, cultural and religious, authorial and literary worlds of the play, critical lenses, and how to weave AO4 into the argument rather than bolt it on.">
  <div class="part-head">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kicker">Assessment Objective 4 &middot; a third of the mark</p>
      <h1>Context</h1>
      <p class="lede prose">
        AO4 carries ten of the thirty marks, so context is not decoration: it is a full third of
        what the examiner is looking for. But the marks are not paid for facts about 1606. They are
        paid for the relationship between the play and its world, shown at the point where that world
        changes what a line means. Context belongs inside the topic sentence and is looped back to in
        the analysis. Woven, never bolted on.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap prose">

      <h2 style="margin-top:0;">Historical: a play written in the shadow of a plot</h2>
      <p>
        Macbeth was written for a Scotland that had just arrived on the English throne. James VI of
        Scotland became James I of England at the Union of the Crowns in 1603, and in November 1605 a
        group of Catholic conspirators very nearly blew him and his Parliament apart. The Gunpowder
        Plot made regicide the single most charged subject in the country, and the trials that
        followed in 1606 turned on the doctrine of equivocation: the Jesuit Henry Garnet was
        condemned partly for defending the idea that a person might swear a true-sounding oath while
        meaning something else before God. A play about the murder of a king by a trusted subject,
        full of speech that means two things at once, was not a costume drama for its first audience.
        It was the news, dramatised. The 1604 witchcraft statute had also made trafficking with
        spirits a capital crime, so the sisters on stage were not quaint: they were felons the state
        had just decided to hang. Behind all of this sits the real eleventh-century Macbeth, a king
        who in fact reigned for years, whom Shakespeare compresses and darkens because the point is
        not the history but the anxiety.
      </p>
      <p class="small"><strong>In the play.</strong> The Porter scene, Act 2, Scene 3, drops the word
        &lsquo;equivocator&rsquo; into a comic riff on the exact treason doctrine on trial the year the
        play appeared. The knocking at the gate is the state arriving at the door of a house that has
        just killed a king.</p>

      <h2>Social: the household as a kingdom in miniature</h2>
      <p>
        Jacobean society was ordered by rank, loyalty and hospitality, and the most sacred bond of
        all was the duty a host owed a guest and a subject owed his king. To harm a man who had eaten
        under your roof, who was also your kinsman, who was also your sovereign, was to break every
        tie at once. This is why Macbeth does not simply commit a murder: he violates the whole social
        contract in a single act, and the audience feels it as a kind of blasphemy against ordinary
        life. Gender ran through the same order. A wife was expected to be subordinate and nurturing,
        so a woman who calls on spirits to strip her of tenderness is not just frightening in herself,
        she is an image of a world turned upside down. Court life, honour and reputation are the
        currency the Macbeths trade in, and the tragedy is partly the story of two people who win the
        top of the order and find it worthless.
      </p>
      <p class="small"><strong>In the play.</strong> Macbeth himself names the offence before he acts:
        he is &lsquo;here in double trust&rsquo; (Act 1, Scene 7) as kinsman and host, the man
        &lsquo;who should against his murderer shut the door, not bear the knife myself&rsquo;. The
        social horror is scripted into his own conscience.</p>

      <h2>Cultural and religious: providence, demons and the fear of chaos</h2>
      <p>
        This was a Protestant country that read the Catholic plot of 1605 as proof of hell working in
        the world, and it took the supernatural seriously as theology, not superstition. James I had
        himself written <em>Daemonologie</em>, a treatise arguing that witches were real agents of the
        Devil, so demonic influence was a matter of learned belief at the very top. Underneath ran the
        idea of providence and divine order, often pictured as the Great Chain of Being, in which
        every creature had its ordained place and a crime against the king was a crime against God and
        nature together. When order is broken, the culture expected nature itself to convulse. The
        supernatural in the play is therefore not spectacle bolted on for thrills: it is the visible
        sign of a moral universe reacting to sin, and the terror of the sisters is the terror of a
        world where the Devil can tell you the truth in order to damn you.
      </p>
      <p class="small"><strong>In the play.</strong> The apparitions of Act 4, Scene 1 speak in double
        meanings that are true and lethal at once: &lsquo;none of woman born&rsquo; and &lsquo;great
        Birnam wood to high Dunsinane hill&rsquo; are honest words that betray, exactly the demonology
        James described.</p>

      <h2>Authorial: written for a king by the King&rsquo;s Men</h2>
      <p>
        Shakespeare did not write in a vacuum, and knowing who paid him sharpens every choice. His
        company had been taken under royal patronage and renamed the King&rsquo;s Men, so a play first
        performed around 1606 was written by servants of the very king it flatters. Shakespeare drew
        his plot from Holinshed&rsquo;s <em>Chronicles</em>, then bent the source to please his patron:
        the historical Banquo was a co-conspirator in the murder, but Shakespeare makes him noble and
        innocent because James believed himself descended from Banquo&rsquo;s line. Reading the play as
        a made object, shaped for a particular king at a particular moment, is itself an AO4 move: it
        turns &lsquo;Shakespeare shows&rsquo; into &lsquo;Shakespeare chooses, and here is why&rsquo;.
      </p>
      <p class="small"><strong>In the play.</strong> When Macbeth asks in horror whether the show of
        kings will &lsquo;stretch out&rsquo; that far, Act 4, Scene 1 holds a mirror up to James in the
        audience and promises Banquo&rsquo;s house will reign for ever.</p>

      <h2>Literary: a tragedy that swallows a chronicle</h2>
      <p>
        Macbeth belongs to a tradition, and naming it well lets you argue about form rather than just
        plot. It is a tragedy in the line that runs from the Greeks, built to carry a great man from
        height to ruin and to end in the audience&rsquo;s pity and fear. It is also a chronicle history,
        a usurpation play about the taking and losing of a crown, so it fuses two shapes at once. Its
        method is a mixture of high poetry and stage spectacle: the same play gives us witches, a
        banquet and a severed head, and some of the most inward verse ever written. Above all,
        Shakespeare replaces the classical chorus with the soliloquy, letting a murderer think aloud so
        that we are trapped inside the mind of the man we watch damn himself. To write about the play
        as literature is to write about these forms doing their work.
      </p>
      <p class="small"><strong>In the play.</strong> The soliloquy carries the tragedy&rsquo;s inward
        turn: &lsquo;is this a dagger which I see before me&rsquo; (Act 2, Scene 1) makes the audience
        the only witness to a conscience breaking, a job the chorus could never do.</p>

      <h2>Critical lenses: a way to level up AO4</h2>
      <p>
        Beyond the world of 1606, the play has been read through later frameworks, and using one well
        can lift a paragraph from competent to distinctive. A <strong>feminist</strong> reading asks
        what the play does with gender: how it ties power to masculinity, punishes a woman who reaches
        for it, and lets Lady Macbeth&rsquo;s force curdle into madness once she has served the plot. A
        <strong>psychological</strong> reading treats the daggers, the ghost and the hand-washing as
        the workings of guilt made visible, tracing how the mind stages what the conscience cannot
        say. A <strong>historical and social</strong> reading, the one closest to AO4, sets the play
        back among the anxieties of its first audience, reading the witches through the witchcraft
        statute and the murder through the Gunpowder Plot.
      </p>
      <div class="box think">
        <h3>A lens is a tool, not a badge</h3>
        <p>
          Do not announce &lsquo;a feminist critic would say&rsquo; and move on: that is wearing the
          lens as a badge. Use the frame to build an argument you then prove from the text. The reading
          has to earn its keep in the analysis of language, form and structure, or it is just a label.
          Choose the lens that makes your evidence say more, and drop it the moment it stops helping.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2>How to weave context</h2>
      <p>
        The difference between a mid-band and a top-band essay is usually not how much context you know
        but where you put it. Weak essays quarantine context in a paragraph of its own; strong essays
        let it frame the point and then return to it. Two habits do most of the work.
      </p>
      <p>
        First, the <strong>contextualised topic sentence</strong>: open the paragraph with a claim that
        already carries the context, so the analysis is aimed from the first word. Instead of
        &lsquo;Lady Macbeth is ambitious&rsquo;, try: &lsquo;Because a Jacobean wife was expected to be
        her husband&rsquo;s subordinate, Lady Macbeth&rsquo;s command of the murder would have struck
        the first audience as a threat to the order of the household itself.&rsquo; The context now sets
        the terms of the reading.
      </p>
      <p>
        Second, <strong>looping back</strong>: after the close analysis, return to that contextual angle
        to explain the effect. Having quoted her call to be unsexed, you might close: &lsquo;In a
        culture that pictured every crime against nature as a crack in the divine order, her wish to be
        emptied of tenderness reads less as personal cruelty than as a small act of cosmic rebellion,
        which is why the play must later break her.&rsquo; The paragraph opens and closes on context, and
        the analysis lives inside it. Notice that neither sentence stops to lecture on history: the fact
        is carried in a clause and put straight to work on meaning.
      </p>
      <div class="box exam">
        <h3>Take this into the coursework</h3>
        <p>
          Every paragraph you write should open with a contextualised topic sentence and loop back to
          it once the analysis is done. Naming a device is labelling, not analysis, and dropping a date
          is not context: both only count when they change what a line means. See how this fits the
          three set questions and the marking on the <a href="/coursework/">coursework page</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

